            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                But when we arrived in Guatemala City, the mission president, President Amado, called us in and he said, “We need someone to go out into the branches and teach them how to keep records and send in their reports, because they’re not doing it. So we want you to go out and do that. You’ve got your car.” We drove to Guatemala in our car and had it with us. We were amazed, because neither Kenneth or I had ever been a secretary or a clerk, and there we were. They gave us that responsibility.



            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory3-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory3');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory3" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    We worked with the mission president’s brother for a month, and he took us out to all the branches in the Guatemala City Mission, which was about 20–25 branches we were responsible for. We went out and visited each of the branches, and we had to learn how to do the reports ourselves. We had quite an adventure, because about once a month we would go out and visit those branches and visit with the branch president and teach them how to do the records and make their reports. Oftentimes, we would pull open the file drawer in the branch office, and there would be cobwebs in there because they had not been used. <br /><br />

                    One time we went into one of the branches, and before we could begin our work we had to get a foot-long lizard off the pulpit so we could start. <br /><br />

                    We felt like we were successful in teaching. We learned first and then we taught the presidents in our broken Spanish how to do those reports. When we left, the percentage of reports that were being sent in was way, way high. We felt like we had been blessed to do some good work down there. That was the main thing we were called to do. <br /><br />

                    We had so much adventure in that mission. I smile whenever I think about the Guatemala City Mission. It was special.
